Date: Sun 20 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Australian Broadcasting Company, Sun 20 Feb 2005 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200502/s1306821.htm>

Avian influenza has "pandemic potential"
----------------------------------------
One of the world's top researchers [Dr. Nancy Cox from CDC Atlanta]
investigating outbreaks of avian influenza in South-East Asia says
she is extremely concerned by the scientific evidence emerging about
the virus. Dr. Nancy Cox is the Head of the Influenza Division of the
United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).
She says research now shows that bird flu is capable of mutating into
a form that can spread from humans to humans. "We have found that,
for the 2003 virus, the virus had actually changed its receptive
[receptor] binding [site] or its ability to bind to the receptors
that are in human cells," she said. "This shows that the virus can
actually change in such a way, or has actually changed in the past in
such a way, that might make it more easily transmitted from person to
person."
She also says the recent spurt of human infections increases the
likelihood that a mutant strain would arise that could spread between
humans. "It's impossible to predict what the consequences would be.
We might have a relatively mild pandemic like we did in 1968," Dr.
Cox said. "Alternatively, we could have a relatively severe pandemic
as occurred in 1918 or perhaps even worse."
--
